aa(lp267
VNow, this ideology gets policed by this one very dangerous question,
p268
aVwhich is, "What percentage of my donation goes to the cause versus overhead?"
p269
aVThere are a lot of problems with this question.
p270
aVI'm going to just focus on two.
p271
aVFirst, it makes us think that overhead is a negative,
p272
aVthat it is somehow not part of the cause.
p273
aVBut it absolutely is, especially if it's being used for growth.
p274
aVNow, this idea that overhead is somehow an enemy of the cause
p275
aVcreates this second, much larger problem,
p276
aVwhich is, it forces organizations to go without the overhead things
p277
aVthey really need to grow,
p278
aVin the interest of keeping overhead low.
p279
aa(lp280
VSo we've all been taught that charities should spend
p281
aVas little as possible on overhead things like fundraising
p282
aVunder the theory that, well, the less money you spend on fundraising,
p283
aVthe more money there is available for the cause.
p284
aVWell, that's true if it's a depressing world
p285
aVin which this pie cannot be made any bigger.
p286
aVBut if it's a logical world in which investment in fundraising
p287
aVactually raises more funds and makes the pie bigger,
p288
aVthen we have it precisely backwards,
p289
aVand we should be investing more money, not less, in fundraising,
p290
aVbecause fundraising is the one thing
p291
aVthat has the potential to multiply the amount of money
p292
aVavailable for the cause that we care about so deeply.
p293
aa(lp294
VI'll give you two examples.
p295
aVWe launched the AIDSRides
p296
aVwith an initial investment of 50,000 dollars in risk capital.
p297
aVWithin nine years, we had multiplied that 1,982 times,
p298
aVinto 108 million dollars after all expenses, for AIDS services.
p299
aVWe launched the breast cancer three-days
p300
aVwith an initial investment of 350,000 dollars in risk capital.
p301
aVWithin just five years, we had multiplied that 554 times,
p302
aVinto 194 million dollars after all expenses,
p303
aVfor breast cancer research.
p304
aVNow, if you were a philanthropist really interested in breast cancer,
p305
aVwhat would make more sense:
p306
aVgo out and find the most innovative researcher in the world
p307
aVand give her 350,000 dollars for research,
p308
aVor give her fundraising department the 350,000 dollars
p309
aVto multiply it into 194 million dollars for breast cancer research?
p310
aV2002 was our most successful year ever.
p311
aVWe netted for breast cancer alone, that year alone,
p312
aV71 million dollars after all expenses.
p313
aVAnd then we went out of business,
p314
aVsuddenly and traumatically.
